%I A397260 #16 Jul 17 2026 00:41:27
%S A397260 1,2,3,4,6,8,12,16,18,24,36,48,68,72,78,96,144,156,168,196,198,288,
%T A397260 378,396,558,576,588,768,792,798,996,998,1584,1596,1794,1998,2688,
%U A397260 2988,3588,3976,3996,4788,4998,5796,5976,5988,7788,7798,7996,7998,9798,9996,15996,17976,17988,19992,19996
%N A397260 Indices of records in A093811.
%C A397260 Motivated in particular by the search for other fixed points of A093811, cf. A397257.
%C A397260 The record values are listed in A397261, see there for further information and graphics.
%C A397260 We conjecture that the following numbers are always in this sequence:
%C A397260   - 8*10^k - 2 and 16*10^k - 4, for all k >= 0,
%C A397260   - 10^k - 4 and 6*10^k - 12, for all k >= 1,
%C A397260   - 10^k - 2, for all k > 4; cf. examples.
%C A397260 A more complete list of simple patterns of numbers that we conjecture to be always in the sequence is as follows: {179...958, 179...976, 179...988, 19...96, 269...988, 29...9898, 29...988, 39...988,, 39...96, 479...988, 49...98, 579...98, 59...9898, 59...976, 59...988, 779...98, 79...988, 79...96, 79...98, 979...98, 9...96, 9...98}. Here, "9...9" means any positive number of digits 9.
%H A397260 M. F. Hasler, <a href="/A397260/b397260.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..172</a>
%e A397260 For n = 10^k - 4, k > 1, divisors are (1, 2, 3, 4, ..., n/4, n/3, n/2, n). The major contributions to A093811(n) come from n/4, n/2 and n which have k-2 or k-1 digits 9, so A007954(n) = 9^(k-1)*6, A007954(n/2) = 4*9^(k-2)*8, A007954(n/4) = 2*4*9^(k-2), for a total of 9^(k-2)*(9*6 + 8*(4+1)) = 9^(k-2)*94 ~ 1.16*9^k. This sets a new record for all k.
%e A397260 For n = 10^k - 2, k > 0, divisors are (1, 2, ..., n/2, n), and with A007954(n) = 9^(k-1)*8 and A007954(n/2) = 4*9^(k-1), A093811(n) ~ 9^k*4/3, which also sets a new record for all k > 4, but not for k = 2 and k = 4 where the additional divisors of 10^k - 4 outweigh the 8/6 and 9/8 advantage of the two largest divisors.
%e A397260 For n = 2*10^k - 4, k > 0, divisors are (1, 2, 4, ..., n/4, n/2, n), and we get A093811(n) >= 9^(k-1)*(6+8+4) = 2*9^k, which also sets a new record.
%e A397260 While n = 2*10^k - 2 also sets a record for k < 7, due to a large number of divisors, this is no more the case for k > 6, where the divisors n/3, n/6, ... contribute less than the divisor n/4 of 2*10^k - 4.
%o A397260 (PARI) L397260=List(1); A397260(n)={while(n>#L397260, my(k=L397260[#L397260], m=A093811(k)); until(A093811(k++)>m,); listput(L397260,k)); L397260[n]}
%Y A397260 Cf. A007954 (digital product dp(n)), A093811 (Sum_{d|n} dp(d)), A397257 (fixed points of A093811).
%K A397260 nonn,base,new
%O A397260 1,2
%A A397260 _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 11 2026
